revision.text:
{{Double image stack|right|Oni-no-Manaita, zenkei.jpg|Oni-no-Secchin, zenkei.jpg|250|{{Center|Oni-no-Manaita (Top) and Oni-no-Secchin (Bottom)}}}} '''Oni-no-Manaita''' (鬼の俎) and '''Oni-no-Secchin''' (鬼の雪隠) are granite stone structures located in {{ill|Asuka, Nara|ja|明日香村|12=draft|12=draft}}, Noguchi (Oni-no-Manaita) and Hirata (Oni-no-Secchin), {{ill|Takaichi District|ja|高市郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft|12=draft}}. They are designated by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft|12=draft}} as associated tombs (陪冢) of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|ja|欽明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Umemiyama Kofun|ja|梅山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} (Hinokuma Sakai Mausoleum).
== Overview ==
Oni-no-Manaita is situated on an elevated area beside a walking path through farmland, while Oni-no-Secchin lies at the base of the hill across the path. Although separated by a few dozen meters in a straight line, the two are believed to have originally been part of a single stone burial chamber (石槨) of a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}, with the mound having disappeared and the structure splitting into two. Initially, they formed a {{ill|Cave Tomb-style stone chamber|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, with the lid stone (Oni-no-Secchin) and the base stone (Oni-no-Manaita) made from granite. The base stone retains traces of where the door stone of the Cave Tomb-style chamber would have been set.
Notably, the base stone contains several mortise holes, believed to have been added later in an attempt to cut and reuse the stone as construction material.
The dimensions are as follows: * '''Base stone (Manaita)''': Approx. 4.5m in length, 2.7m in width, and 1m in thickness. * '''Lid stone (Secchin)''': Approx. 1.5m in internal width and 1.3m in height.
According to local folklore, an oni (demon) inhabited the Wind Forest area (風の森) and would trick and capture travelers, consuming them. It is said that the oni used the "Manaita" for cooking and the "Secchin" as a lavatory.
There is also a theory that the Oni-no-Manaita and Oni-no-Secchin represent a double tomb (双墓). According to historical records, an additional, slightly smaller base stone once lay adjacent to the current Manaita but was broken into smaller pieces during the Meiji era and repurposed as decorative stones for a private garden. This theory posits that the Oni-no-Manaita and Oni-no-Secchin Kofun formed one tomb, while the neighboring stone chamber constituted a matching counterpart. The fragments from the adjacent stone chamber were later recovered and are now displayed in the outdoor exhibit of the {{ill|Kashihara Archaeological Institute|ja|橿原考古学研究所|12=draft|12=draft}} Museum.
<gallery> File:Oni-no-Manaita and Oni-no-Secchin, 3D-B.jpg|Overhead view (Manaita and Secchin rejoined) File:Oni-no-Manaita and Oni-no-Secchin, 3D-N.jpg|Exploded view (Manaita and Secchin rejoined) </gallery>
